  "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?",
  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety that certain groups face when they might be seen as confirming or denying stereotypes about their abilities, particularly regarding race, gender, or ethnicity. As an immigrant plumber with a background that doesn't align with traditional STEM stereotypes, I find this concept relevant because it affects how people perceive themselves and perform under pressure.\n\nFor instance, in my daily work, I often encounter clients who have preconceived notions about trades being male-dominated or unskilled. This is similar to stereotype threat; when we're judged based on group characteristics, our performance can suffer due to anxiety. In STEM fields like engineering or tech, this manifests as women or minority groups feeling anxious in situations where stereotypes suggest they are less capable.\n\nI believe it's crucial to address stereotype threat because it undermines not just personal confidence but also broader societal goals. When people don't feel safe or valued, their potential doesn't fully realize. My own anxiety sometimes affects my work, so supporting environments that reduce pressure and foster inclusivity makes sense for everyone involved.",
